reviewText: Classic violent sexual cartoon. So funny and great one liners. A must have for bad movie fans. I wish that I could get this on DVD. Voices of Bill Murrey and James Belushi. Tarzoon and June living in the jungle. June is kidnapped by phalic guards(big animated penises) and Tarzoon must rescue her from the evil queen that wants her hair. Must see to believe. If you liked "Fritz the Cat" you will love this one.

reviewText: This Tarzan spoof may have been racy back in 1975, but it looks tame today. Normally this sort of "raunchy" humor would have me lying on the floor clutching my stomach with tears of laughter streaming down my face. I didn't laugh once.An American edit of a French cartoon with American voiceovers; the "plot" centres on Shame's efforts to rescue his girlfriend June from the movie's anatomically incorrect villain, who resembles a bald Cruella De Vil. However there is one memorable scene of marching male members (that's correct), complete with army helmets! It's safe to presume I'm not ruining anything by saying they don't fire bullets. The 10 second sequence showing the creation of these soldiers is the only part of the entire film which is mildly funny but the ending is original, to say the least and is solely what earns the movie an extra star.There are also a couple of memorable scenes involving an enthusiastically amorous chimp. John Belushi and Bill Murray made their film debuts here (or rather their voices did). But in the long run you're  better off watching some SOUTH PARK reruns instead.

reviewText: I was hoping that when I received this DVD, that I'd be getting an unedited version of this movie. Unfortunetly, this is a soft R movie with the bulk of the really bawdy humor removed. Unless you've seen the unedited version (as I have), you'd wonder what is going on some of the times. Nevertheless, this does have a lot of humor still & if you can stand the jump-cuts, you may enjoy this bawdy satire.

reviewText: Ah, 70's Adult Animation. Fritz the Cat, Heavy Traffic, Dirty Duck, The Nine Lives of Fritz The Cat... and this... yeeech... it should have been so much better...Picha is a Belgian animator who was of some popularity in France, however whatever appeal this film might have had seems lost in the translation. Visually, it's style is rather crude compared to Ralph (Fritz the Cat) Bakshi, and the evil queen's army of marching giant schlongs stops being funny after the intial novelty wears off (in about 30 seconds). There's some funny business, but not enough to save this stinker.Blame Micheal (Mr. Mike's Mondo Video) O'Donahue, famed Saturday Night Live writer for that. The script must have been thrown out the window, or perhaps Mr. Mike was never given a copy, or didn't understand French, and made it all up as he went along. One gets the idea that there was some sort of pointed social commentary guised in comedy originally invested in the film, but that might be purest optimism. It could be that not even the otherwise bizzarely hilarious cutting wit of Mr. Mike would have saved this dog.The talents of John Belushi and Brian Doyle Murray are completely wasted here, Belushi gets about four minutes of audio time, and one can't even tell what part Murray voiced-over. I wouldn't bother with it, and I would especially advise avoiding the edited R-Rated version; it cuts most of the few laughs found in the film. Better animated films than this are a dime a dozen. Pick one of them and leave this dog to lie.
